Etymology[edit]

From cū̆stōs.

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /kuːsˈtoː.di.oː/, [kuːs̠ˈt̪oː.d̪i.oː] or IPA(key): /kusˈtoː.di.oː/, [kʊs̠ˈt̪oː.d̪i.oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /kusˈto.di.o/, [kusˈt̪ɔː.d̪i.ɔ]

Verb[edit]

cū̆stōdiō (present infinitive cū̆stōdīre, perfect active cū̆stōdīvī or cū̆stōdiī, supine cū̆stōdītum); fourth conjugation

  1. I guard.
    • 405 CE, Jerome, Vulgate Exodus.20.6:
      et faciens misericordiam in millia his qui diligunt me, et custodiunt praecepta mea.
      and shewing mercy unto thousands of them that love me, and keep my commandments.

Notes[edit]

Root vowel length uncertain due to unclear etymology, lack of inscriptional evidence and conflicting evidence from Romance languages.
